 @Boogeymann  No, it does not play smooth, that's just placebo effect. All frame gen does is visually smoothing the game by creating fake frames.

Indiana Jones runs at best at 70 fps for you. You can enable frame gen, but it still will run at a maximum of 70 fps, likely lower due to overhead from running frame gen.

I can explain why fake AI frames don't matter

 @Orcawhale1  nah, it's not a 1050, I've owned both and I'm still using the 1060 3g from 2016 just fine now. The difference wasn't as big.

I do regret buying the gtx 770 over the r9 290 a few years before, I don't regret the 1060 one bit, even with 3gb, it served me well, even if the 580 was well above and aged much better, I sold that eventually.

I've been through a lot of cards of that period, including a vega64 and a gtx 1080.

 @awebuser5914   I don't want DLSS4 framegen, absolutely no use for it.

What i dislike about 20-series is total lack of support for reBAR, plus too modest an RT performance.

Power efficiency isn't really that big a deal, you can just trim it down with little lost in terms of performance, and in desktop use (non-gaming) they consume barely nothing anyway and it doesn't change that much generation on generation.

 @awebuser5914  you’re correct IF it’s a 5.0x16 card going into a 4.0 slot, but a 5.0x8 card in a 4.0 slot will be limited to half the maximum bandwidth of 4.0.

Edit:
I should clarify that I’m just speculating on the performance of the 8gb models. I doubt the card is fast enough to outrun 16gb
